    "raw_text": {
        "question": "Imagine launching a toy rocket straight up into the sky, and its path through the air can be tracked with a formula based on time since launch. The formula for its flight path is given by the equation where the height of the rocket at any time 't' (in seconds) is determined by $h=200t - 4.9t^{2}$, while the horizontal distance at any time 't' is determined by 'd=80t'. How high does the rocket go at its highest point before it starts to come back down?\n\nRetrieved documents:\n[Document 1]\n\\begin{definition}[Definition:Thrust]\nThe '''thrust''' of a rocket is defined as the product of the exhaust velocity and the rate at which its fuel is being consumed:\n:$\\mathbf t = \\mathbf b \\paren {\\dfrac {\\d m} {\\d t} }$\nwhere:\n:$\\mathbf b$ is the exhaust velocity\n:$m$ is the mass of the rocket as a function of time $t$.\n\\end{definition}\n\n[Document 2]\n\\section{Derivative of Composite Function}\nTags: Differential Calculus\n\n\\begin{theorem}\nLet $f, g, h$ be continuous real functions such that:\n:$\\forall x \\in \\R: \\map h x = \\map {f \\circ g} x = \\map f {\\map g x}$\nThen:\n:$\\map {h'} x = \\map {f'} {\\map g x} \\map {g'} x$\nwhere $h'$ denotes the derivative of $h$.\nUsing the $D_x$ notation:\n:$\\map {D_x} {\\map f {\\map g x} } = \\map {D_{\\map g x} } {\\map f {\\map g x} } \\map {D_x} {\\map g x}$\nThis is often informally referred to as the '''chain rule (for differentiation)'''.\n\\end{theorem}\n\n\\begin{proof}\nLet $\\map g x = y$, and let:\n{{begin-eqn}}\n{{eqn | l = \\map g {x + \\delta x}\n      | r = y + \\delta y\n      | c = \n}}\n{{eqn | ll= \\leadsto\n      | l = \\delta y\n      | r = \\map g {x + \\delta x} - \\map g x\n      | c = \n}}\n{{end-eqn}}\nThus:\n:$\\delta y \\to 0$ as $\\delta x \\to 0$\nand:\n:$(1): \\quad \\dfrac {\\delta y} {\\delta x} \\to \\map {g'} x$\nThere are two cases to consider:\n\\end{proof}\n\n\n\n[Document 3]\n\\section{Acceleration of Rocket in Outer Space}\nTags: Rocket Science, Dynamics\n\n\\begin{theorem}\nLet $B$ be a rocket travelling in outer space.\nLet the velocity of $B$ at time $t$ be $\\mathbf v$.\nLet the mass of $B$ at time $t$ be $m$.\nLet the exhaust velocity of $B$ be constant at $\\mathbf b$.\nThen the acceleration of $B$ at time $t$ is given by:\n:$\\mathbf a = \\dfrac 1 m \\paren {-\\mathbf b \\dfrac {\\d m} {\\d t} }$\n\\end{theorem}\n\n\\begin{proof}\nFrom Motion of Rocket in Outer Space, the equation of motion of $B$ is given by:\n:$(1): \\quad m \\dfrac {\\d \\mathbf v} {\\d t} = -\\mathbf b \\dfrac {\\d m} {\\d t}$\nBy definition, the acceleration of $B$ is its rate of change of velocity:\n:$\\mathbf a = \\dfrac {\\d \\mathbf v} {\\d t}$\nThe result follows by substituting $\\mathbf a$ for $\\dfrac {\\d \\mathbf v} {\\d t}$ and dividing by $m$.\n{{qed}}\n\\end{proof}\n\n\n\n[Document 4]\n\\begin{definition}[Definition:Burnout Height]\nLet $R$ be a rocket which is propelled by backwards expulsion of the exhaust products of the burning of its internal fuel supply.\nLet $R$ be fired straight up from the surface of a planet.\nThe '''burnout height''' of $R$ is the height attained by $R$ at the instant when its fuel has become exhausted.\n\\end{definition}\n\n[Document 5]\n\\begin{definition}[Definition:Travelling With and Against the Flow Puzzle]\nA '''travelling with and against the flow puzzle''' is a problem of the form:\n:A body travels a certain distance $d$ through a medium in the same direction as the constant flow of that medium in a given time $t_1$.\n:The same body travels the same distance $d$ in the opposite direction, that is against the flow of the medium, in a given time $t_2$.\n:How long would it take the body to travel $d$ in absence of any such flow?\nVariants give:\n:the time taken for the body to travel at the same speed as the medium\n:the time taken for the body to travel either with or against the medium\nwhere the object of the exercise is to work out how long it takes to travel in the opposite direction.\nCategory:Definitions/Classic Problems\n\\end{definition}",
        "response": "To determine the maximum height the toy rocket reaches before it starts to descend, we need to analyze the given height equation:\n\n\\[ h(t) = 200t - 4.9t^2 \\]\n\nThis equation represents the height \\( h \\) of the rocket as a function of time \\( t \\). The rocket reaches its maximum height when its vertical velocity becomes zero. To find this, we first need to find the velocity function by taking the derivative of the height function with respect to time:\n\n\\[ v(t) = \\frac{dh}{dt} = \\frac{d}{dt}(200t - 4.9t^2) \\]\n\nUsing basic differentiation rules:\n\n\\[ v(t) = 200 - 9.8t \\]\n\nThe rocket reaches its maximum height when the velocity \\( v(t) \\) is zero:\n\n\\[ 200 - 9.8t = 0 \\]\n\nSolving for \\( t \\):\n\n\\[ 9.8t = 200 \\]\n\\[ t = \\frac{200}{9.8} \\]\n\\[ t \\approx 20.41 \\text{ seconds} \\]\n\nNow, we substitute this time back into the height equation to find the maximum height:\n\n\\[ h(20.41) = 200(20.41) - 4.9(20.41)^2 \\]\n\nCalculating each term:\n\n\\[ 200(20.41) = 4082 \\]\n\\[ 4.9(20.41)^2 = 4.9(416.5681) \\approx 2041.18 \\]\n\nSubtracting the second term from the first:\n\n\\[ h(20.41) \\approx 4082 - 2041.18 \\]\n\\[ h(20.41) \\approx 2040.82 \\text{ meters} \\]\n\nTherefore, the rocket reaches its highest point at approximately **2040.82 meters** before it starts to descend."
    },
